<DOC><DOCNO> WSJ880601-0164 </DOCNO><HL> Credit Ratings: New York City Bonds Upgraded by Moody's </HL><SO> </SO><IN> BON </IN><DATELINE> NEW YORK  </DATELINE><TEXT>   Moody's Investors Service Inc. raised its ratings on a number of New York City bond issues, citing the city's consistent and responsible financial performance.    &quot;A decade after the fiscal crisis, the general-obligation bond rating of New York City has achieved its pre-crisis level,&quot; Moody's said. &quot;The city has consistently displayed a willingness and ability to implement systems which have provided for responsible and successful financial management. . . . Financial strengths and controls were tested with the stock market crash and found to be satisfactory.&quot; About $19.3 billion of debt is affected by the changes.    The rating agency increased to single-A from Baa-1 its rating of the following bond issues: City of New York (general obligation), New York City Housing Authority (guaranteed by the City), New York City Educational Construction Fund series 1972 A, and Municipal Water Finance for the City of New York.    Moody's raised to double-A from single-A-1 its rating for first and second resolution general obligation/special tax bonds of the Municipal Assistance Corp. for the City of New York. </TEXT></DOC>